# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cirebon-shipwreck
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] The **Admiralty Islands** are an archipelago group of 40 islands in the Bismarck Archipelago, to the north of New Guinea in the South Pacific Ocean.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] These are also sometimes known as the **Manus Islands**, after the largest island of the chain.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] These rainforest-covered islands constitute Manus Province, the smallest and least-populous province of Papua New Guinea, in its Islands Region.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] The province had a population of 60,485 at the 2011 Census.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] Many of the smaller Admiralty Islands are atolls and uninhabited.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] The larger islands in the center of the group are Manus Island and Los Negros Island.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] The other larger islands are Tong Island, Pak Island, Rambutyo Island and Lou Island to the east, Mbuke Island to the south and Bipi Island to the west of Manus Island.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] Baluan Island, to the south of Manus Island, is the main island of the Pam Islands, where the Baluan-Pam language is spoken.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] Other islands that have been noted as significant places in the history of Manus include Ndrova Island, Pityilu Island and Ponam Island.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] The temperature of the Admiralty Islands varies little throughout the year, reaching daily highs of 30–32 °C (86–90 °F) and 20–24 °C (68–75 °F) at night.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] Average annual rainfall is 3,382 mm (133 in) and is somewhat seasonal, with June–August being the wettest months.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] Manus reaches an elevation of 700 m (2,300 ft) and is volcanic in origin and probably broke through the ocean's surface in the late Miocene, 8–10 million years ago.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] The substrate of the island is either directly volcanic or from uplifted coral limestone.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] The main town in the islands is Lorengau on Manus, connected by road to an airport on nearby Los Negros Island, otherwise transport around the islands is by boat.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] There is little tourism, although the seas are attractive to divers, including Jean-Michel Cousteau who spent time on nearby Wuvulu Island in the 1970s.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] Due to the isolated location, the rain forests of the Admiralty Islands are home to rare and endemic species of birds, bats and other animals, and are considered a separate ecoregion, the **Admiralty Islands lowland rain forests**.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] The majority of the forests on Manus still remain, but some of the smaller islands have been cleared for coconut farming.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] The typical tree species are various *Calophyllum* and *Sararanga* species.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] The 58.5 km2 (22.6 sq mi) Ndrolowa Wildlife Management Area was created in March 1985 south of Lorengau on Manus Island and contains both terrestrial and marine regions.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] A further 240 km2 (93 sq mi) protected area has been established around the highest mountain on Manus, Mount Dremsel, but the level of protection remains undetermined in the UNEP World Database on Protected Areas.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] Three of the bird species endemic to Admiralty Islands have been listed as vulnerable in the IUCN Red List: Manus fantail (*Rhipidura semirubra*), superb pitta (*Pitta superba*) and Manus masked owl (*Tyto manusi*), and the Manus dwarf kingfisher (*Ceyx dispar*) listed as near threatened.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] Three other birds are endemic to Admiralty Islands but are classified as non-threatened or least concern: white-naped friarbird (*Philemon albitorques*), Manus monarch (*Monarcha infelix*) and Manus hawk owl (*Ninox meeki*).
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] The islands are home to two endemic *Cornufer* frogs (*Cornufer admiraltiensis* and *Cornufer latro*) and four lizards, while the emerald green snail of Manus was the first terrestrial snail to be listed as vulnerable by the IUCN.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] Along with New Guinea, the Bismarck Archipelago and the Solomon Islands Archipelago, the Admiralty Islands were first inhabited approximately 40,000 years ago, in the initial wave of migration out of Southeast Asia that also populated Australia.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] This early society appears to have cultivated taro, and to have deliberately introduced wild animals from New Guinea such as bandicoots and large rats.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] Obsidian was gathered and traded throughout the Admiralty Islands archipelago.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] The Lapita culture arose around 3,500 years ago, and its extent ranged from the Admiralty Islands to Tonga and Samoa.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] Its origins are contested, but it may well have been a product of another wave of migration from Southeast Asia.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] Lapita society featured renowned pottery, stilt houses, the introduction of domestic animals such as pigs, dogs, and chickens, and substantial developments in agriculture and boat technology, allowing long-distance trade to develop.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] Lapita society, as a distinct culture and extended trade network, collapsed around 2,000 years ago.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] The first European to visit the islands was the Spanish navigator Álvaro de Saavedra when trying to return from Tidore to New Spain in the summer of 1528.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] Saavedra charted Manus as *Urays la Grande*.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] Its visit was also reported in 1616 by the Dutch navigator Willem Schouten.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] The name 'Admiralty Islands' was devised by Captain Philip Carteret of the British Royal Navy in 1767.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] Between 1884 and 1914 the area was administered as a German colony.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] In November 1914, the islands were occupied by troops of the Australian Naval and Military Expeditionary Force landed from the SS *Siar*.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] A few shots fired from a machine gun on *Siar* over the heads of the tiny German garrison at Lorengau were the last shots fired in the battle.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] After the war, the islands were governed by the Commonwealth of Australia under a League of Nations mandate.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] Japanese troops landed on Manus Island on 7 April 1942.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] In 1944, Japanese forces occupying the islands were attacked and defeated by Allied forces in Operation Brewer.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] Subsequently, a large American airbase and Manus Naval Base was built at Lombrum near Lorengau.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] Following Papuan independence in 1975, the Admiralty Islands became part of Papua New Guinea.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/admiralty-islands] They became the Manus Province of the Islands Region in Papua New Guinea.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/alingano-maisu] The concept for *Alingano Maisu* came about in 2001 when two Hawaiian voyaging groups, the Polynesian Voyaging Society and Na Kalai Waʻa Moku o Hawaiʻi, met with Piailug.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/alingano-maisu] The two hulls of the 56-foot (17 m) vessel were fabricated by the Friends of *Hōkūleʻa* and *Hawaiʻiloa* on Oʻahu and shipped to the Island of Hawaiʻi where Na Kalai Waʻa completed construction of the canoe.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/alingano-maisu] The Polynesian Voyaging Society provided much of the funding for the voyaging aspect of the project as well as an escort boat to help sail the canoe to Satawal.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/alingano-maisu] The canoe is home-ported on the island of Yap under the command of Piailug's son, Sesario Sewralur.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/alingano-maisu] Accompanied by *Hōkūleʻa*, the *Maisu* left Kawaihae, Hawaii, on January 18, 2007.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/alingano-maisu] After stops in the Marshall Islands, Pohnpei, and Chuuk, the Maisu reached Satawal on March 15, 2007.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/alingano-maisu] On March 18, while on Satawal, five native Hawaiian navigators on the voyage were inducted into pwo, a sacred Micronesian brotherhood of master navigators.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/alingano-maisu] In June 2008, Palau Community College announced that there will be a one-year program in traditional non-instrumental navigation on the *Alingano Maisu* under Sesario Sewralur.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The **New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa** is a maritime museum in Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] It is located on Hobson Wharf, adjacent to the Viaduct Harbour in central Auckland.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] It houses exhibitions spanning New Zealand's maritime history, from the first Polynesian explorers and settlers to modern day triumphs at the America's Cup.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The museum focuses on maritime stories of both the Auckland Region and New Zealand, with displays covering topics including immigration, trade, design, innovation, leisure, maritime history, Polynesian voyagers, and the history of the America's Cup.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] In addition to displays and art exhibitions, the New Zealand Maritime Museum collections include historic and cultural artifacts, replicas and working heritage vessels.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The New Zealand Maritime Museum is located on Hobson Wharf on the Auckland waterfront, adjacent to the Viaduct Basin and Princes Wharf.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The entrance of the museum incorporates the Launchman's Building, a structure built in 1920 which formerly housed a number of small boating companies.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The old Launchman's Building (Launch Offices) gained a Category II listing from Heritage New Zealand in 1981.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The main section of the maritime museum in an industrial-inspired structure located on Hobson Wharf.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] Heritage vessels owned by the museum are moored at the museum marina, and launched for sailings around the Waitematā Harbour.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] In 2010, the building won the Auckland Architecture Awards by the New Zealand Institute of Architects.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] Located outside of the Maritime Museum's entrance is *KZ1*, a yacht built to compete in the 1988 America's Cup, gifted to the museum by Fay Richwhite in 1990.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] Currently known as New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa, the museum opened in 1993 as Hobson Wharf: Auckland Maritime Museum.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] In 1996, the museum was renamed the New Zealand National Maritime Museum, a name given by Prime Minister Jim Bolger.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The museum rebranded as Voyager New Zealand Maritime Museum in November 2009, in order to reflect the museum's focus on exploration and discovery.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The organisation's current name, New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa, was adopted in 2014.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The organisation's Māori language name, Hui te Ananui a Tangaroa, was gifted by Hugh Kāwharu of Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei, and means "the Dwelling of Tangaroa", the atua of the oceans.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The establishment of a maritime history museum in Auckland began as a proposal by members of the Auckland Maritime Society, including Bill Laxon, Bob Hawkins, Cliff Hawkins and John Street, and by former members of the Auckland Harbour Board and Union Steam Ship Company.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The society had been established in 1958 as a section of the Auckland Institute and Museum, focused on promoting the study of ships.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] In 1973, the society explored the possibility of establishing a maritime museum on the shores of Lake Pupuke, which was found to be unsuitable.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] In November 1981, the Auckland Maritime Museum was established as a charitable trust.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The Auckland Ferry Terminal, where the museum had been storing archival materials, was explored as a potential site for the museum, but due to the cost of renovations this was decided against.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] In 1984, the museum appointed a director, Gordon Stevenson, former director of the Queen Elizabeth II Army Memorial Museum, and had begun exploring the possibility of using sheds on Princes Wharf.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] Plans for a smaller Princes Wharf museum were halted when the Auckland Harbour Board decided to redevelop Hobson Wharf, with the museum becoming a major part of the redevelopment.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] In 1989, Rodney Wilson was appointed as the new director for the museum, who led fundraising efforts to establish the institution.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] Plans for the museum at Hobson Wharf were announced in February 1989, with construction on the museum beginning in mid-1992.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The museum opened in August 1993, at an estimated cost of NZ$11.1 million.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] Many of the early maritime collections were long-term loans from Auckland War Memorial Museum, or donated items by members of the Auckland Maritime Society.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] While originally focusing on Auckland, the museum later expanded to become a national maritime museum.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] By 1996, financial difficulties led to staff redundancies at the museum, with museum director Richard Cassels resigning during the financial difficulties in 1998.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] In 2001, the New Zealand Government funded the Pacific Discovery Experience, a virtual reality exhibition depicting both the discovery of New Zealand by Polynesian peoples, and the later discovery by Europeans.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] A NZ$8 million extension to the northern end of the museum was built in 2009 to house a permanent exhibition, *Blue Water, Black Magic*, about Sir Peter Blake.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] It includes the original *NZL 32* (*Black Magic*).
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] *Blue Water, Black Magic* was developed in collaboration with Te Papa and Blake's daughter Sarah-Jane Blake.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] In 2010, an extension was added to the museum, housing an exhibition to New Zealand yachting which includes *NZL 32*, the yacht which won the 1995 America's Cup, suspended in the centre of the space.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] By 2018, the museum received approximately 160,000 annual visitors.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The museum was run by New Zealand National Maritime Museum Trust Board until March 2018, when it became a part of Regional Facilities Auckland, an Auckland Council-controlled organisation.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The organisation is now run by Tātaki Auckland Unlimited, the economic development agency of Auckland.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] In 2008, the Auckland Regional Amenities Funding Act was established, which ensured that funding for the New Zealand Maritime Museum was spread across all local councils in the Auckland Region.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] As of 2021, funding for the organisation primarily comes from the Auckland Council.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The first director of the Auckland Maritime Museum Trust was Gordon Stevenson, who was employed in January 1985.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] Rodney Wilson became the museum director in 1989, who was the director of the museum when it opened in 1993.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] In 1994, Wilson left to become the director of the Auckland War Memorial Museum.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] Wilson was replaced by Richard Cassels in the same year, who left in 1998.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] Cassels was followed by chief executive Larry Robbins in 1999, Craig Hobbs in 2007, and Paul Evans in 2008.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] By 2013, Murray Reade had become the chief executive officer.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] In 2013, former director of Toitū Otago Settlers Museum, Linda Wigley, became the director of the maritime museum, overseeing the redevelopment of the museum until her resignation in June 2014.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The current director of the maritime museum, Vincent Lipanovich, has held the position since 2015.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] In 2018, the institution had 166 volunteers, working as tour guides, maintenance and operational crew for heritage vessels, model makers and learning programme assistants.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] Since 2003, personnel from the Royal New Zealand Navy have been occasionally seconded to the museum to assist with maintenance of the ships and exhibition objects.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] In addition, the museum holds collection items focusing on subjects including whaling, modern commercial shipping, lifeboat, pilotage and coastguard services, marine surveying, maritime arts and crafts and maritime recreation.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The museum also operates *Aotearoa One*, launched 2013, described on the museum's website as "a modern take on a traditional waka", which no longer has scheduled sailings.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The museum previously operated the *Rapaki steam crane*, a 1926 floating steam crane, built at Paisley in Scotland for the Lyttelton Harbour Board, which was permanently removed and dismantled in December 2018.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The vessel had been used in active service for three years during World War II, being used to support the United States Navy at New Caledonia.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] The museum has a collection of over 130 watercraft, including the 1933 John L.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] Hacker-designed mahogany and kauri speedboat *Jon-El*, *The Frances*, an early 20th century vessel owned by the Shakespear family, and Paul Caffyn's kayak *Isadora*.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] Other vessels include the *Tainui*, an 1860 whaling vessel, P-class sailing dinghies designed by Harry Highet, *Mammoth*, a moth-class dinghy, and the Karlich hull used by Olympic Gold medalist rowers, the 1972 New Zealand eight.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/aotearoa-one] *Tatarai*, a Baurua voyager canoe from Kiribati built in 1976 by Kiribati islanders and photographer Jim Siers using traditional methods, and sailed from Kiribati to Fiji in 1976, is also held in the museum's collections.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/apilan] Apilan is a native Malay word, not descended from any foreign word.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/apilan] It is also a standalone word, because the syllable is api-lan instead of apil-an.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/apilan] The term comes from Malay word *kota* which in turn comes from the Sanskrit word कोट्ट (kota) which means fort, fortress, castle, fortified house, fortification, works, city, town, or place encircled by walls.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/apilan] The word *mara* may come from Malay word meaning "appear before", "forward", "come", "moved to the front", "forward", and "advanced".
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/apilan] Thus it can be interpreted as "breastwork before a cannon" or "breastwork at the front".
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/apilan] According to the Great Indonesian Dictionary (KBBI), kota mara means (1) Wall on a ship to protect men mounting the cannon (2) Terrace or wall over a castle which a cannon is mounted.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/apilan] Warington Smyth, kota mara means transverse deck bulkhead at stem and stern (of a ship).
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/apilan] *Benteng* itself means fort, battery, or redoubt.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/apilan] Singapore resident John Crawfurd recorded Malay piracy near Singapore waters.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/apilan] The Malay pirate ships of the time were 40–50 feet (12–15 m) long with 15-foot (4.6 m) beam.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/apilan] The decks were made of split *nibong* wood.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/apilan] Smaller pirate craft put up thick plank bulwarks [apilan] when fighting, while larger ones like those of the Lanun people had bamboo ledges hanging over their gunwales, with a protecting breastwork [kota mara] of plaited rattan about 3 feet (0.91 meters) high.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/apilan] A crew might consist of 20–30 men, augmented with oarsmen of captured slaves.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/apilan] Small craft would have nine oars per side; larger ones would be double-banked, with an upper tier of oarsmen seated on the bulwark projection hidden behind rattan breastwork.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/apilan] Pirate armament included a stockade near the bow, with iron or brass 4-pounders, and another stockade aft, generally with two swivel guns.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/apilan] They also might have four or five brass swivels, or rantaka, on each side.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/apilan] They have bamboo shields, and were armed with spears, keris, muskets and other firearms they could get.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] The **archaeology of Indonesia** is the study of the archaeology of the archipelagic realm that today forms the nation of Indonesia, stretching from prehistory through almost two millennia of documented history.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] The ancient Indonesian archipelago was a geographical maritime bridge between the political and cultural centers of Ancient India and Imperial China, and is notable as a part of ancient Maritime Silk Road.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] The first government institution of archaeology was officially formed in 1913 with the establishment of *Oudheidkundige Dienst in Nederlandsch-Indië* (Archaeological Service in the Dutch East Indies) under Professor Dr.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] Today, the national institution of archaeology in Indonesia is the *Pusat Penelitian Arkeologi Nasional* (National Archaeology Research Institute).
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] During the early period of archaeological discovery in Indonesia, from the 16th to the 18th century, ancient statues, temples, ruins and other archaeological sites and artifacts were usually left intact, undisturbed by locals.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] This was mainly due to local taboo and superstitious beliefs connecting statues and ancient ruins with spirits that might cause misfortune.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] For example, two old Javanese chronicles (*babad*) from the 18th century mention cases of bad luck associated with "the mountain of statues", which was actually the ruins of the Borobudur Buddhist monument.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] According to the *Babad Tanah Jawi*, the monument was a fatal factor for Mas Dana, a rebel who revolted against Pakubuwono I, the king of Mataram in 1709.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] It was recorded that the "Redi Borobudur" hill was besieged and the insurgents were defeated and sentenced to death by the king.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] In the *Babad Mataram* (or the *History of the Mataram Kingdom*), the monument was associated with the misfortune of Prince Monconagoro, the crown prince of the Yogyakarta Sultanate in 1757.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] In spite of a taboo against visiting the monument, "he took what is written as *the knight who was captured in a cage* (a Buddha statue in one of the perforated stupas)".
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] Upon returning to his palace, he fell ill and died a day later.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] Another example: the Prambanan and Sewu temple compound is connected to the Javanese legend of Roro Jonggrang; a wondrous folklore about a multitude of demons that built almost a thousand temples, and a prince who cursed a beautiful but cunning princess causing her to become a stone statue.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] Nevertheless, several Javanese Keratons did collect archaeological artifacts, including Hindu-Buddhist statues.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] For example, Keraton Surakarta, Keraton Yogyakarta, and Mangkunegaran collected archaeological artifacts in their palace museums.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] In areas where the Hindu faith survived, especially Bali, archaeological sites such as Goa Gajah cave sanctuary and the Gunung Kawi temples still served their original religious purposes as sacred places of worship.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] Formal archaeological study in Indonesia has its roots in 18th-century Batavia, when a group of Dutch intellectuals established a scientific institution under the name *Bataviaasch Genootschap van Kunsten en Wetenschappen*, (Royal Batavian Society of Arts and Sciences) on 24 April 1778.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] This private body had the aim of promoting research in the field of arts and sciences, especially in history, archaeology, ethnography and physics, and publishing the various findings.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] Sir Thomas Stamford Raffles, the Governor General of British Java (1811 to 1816) had a personal interest in the history, culture, and the antiquity of ancient Java, writing *The History of Java*, which was published in 1817.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] During his administration, the ancient ruins of Borobudur, Prambanan and Trowulan came to light.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] This sparked a wider interest in Javanese archaeology.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] A number of temple ruins were surveyed, recorded and catalogued systematically for the first time.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] However, by the 19th century, the sudden surge of interest in Javanese art had led to the looting of archaeological sites by "souvenir hunters" and thieves.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] This period saw the decapitation of a Buddha's head at Borobudur.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] Of the original 504 ancient Buddha statues in Borobudur, over 300 are damaged (mostly headless), and 43 are missing.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] The looted Borobudur Buddhas' heads were mostly sold abroad, ending up in private collections or acquired by Western museums such as the Tropenmuseum in Amsterdam and The British Museum in London.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] In 1901, the colonial government of the Dutch East Indies set up the *Commissie in Nederlandsch Indie voor Oudheidkundige Onderzoek van Java en Madoera*, headed by Dr J.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] It was officially recognized on 14 June 1913, with the formation of the *Oudheidkundige Dienst in Nederlandsch-Indië* (Archaeological Service of the Dutch East Indies), often abbreviated as "OD", under Professor Dr.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] Kromm is credited as the pioneer who established the organizational foundation of archaeological study in the East Indies.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] The object of this was to attempt to ensure that every archaeological find, discovery, exploration and study was conducted and recorded correctly and in accord with the scientific approach of modern archaeology.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] During Kromm's administration, numbers of journals, books and catalogues were composed and published which systematically recorded the archaeological finds in the colony.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] Several initial restoration works on the temple ruins of Java were also conducted during this period.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] In 1951, the organization of *Djawatan Purbakala* was improved as *Dinas Purbakala* as a part of *Djawatan Kebudajaan Departemen Pendidikan dan Kebudajaan* (Cultural Service of Department of Education and Culture), with independent archaeological offices in Makassar, Prambanan and Bali.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] In 1953, two of the first native Indonesian archaeologists graduated, one of them was R.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] Soekmono, who subsequently succeeded Bernet Kemper as the chief of *Djawatan Poerbakala Repoeblik Indonesia*.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] Later, the national archaeological institution changed to *Lembaga Poerbakala dan Peninggalan Nasional* (Institute of Archaeology and National Heritage) or LPPN.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] In 1975 the LPPN was separated into two institutions: *Direktorat Pemeliharaan dan Pelestarian Peninggalan Sejarah dan Purbakala* which focussed on preservation efforts; and *Pusat Penelitian Purbakala dan Peninggalan Nasional* which focussed on archaeological research.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] In 1980, the institution was changed to *Pusat Penelitian Arkeologi Nasional* (National Archaeological Research Center) under the Ministry of Education and Culture.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] In 2000 the institution was transferred to Ministry of Culture and Tourism.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] In 2005 the institution name was changed to *Pusat Penelitian dan Pengembangan Arkeologi Nasional* (National Archaeological Research and Development Center).
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] In 2012 it changed again to *Pusat Arkeologi Nasional* (National Archaeological Center) with authority transferred back from the Ministry of Tourism to the Ministry of Education and Culture.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] Today, several Indonesian public universities have archaeology study programmes, including Gadjah Mada University in Yogyakarta, University of Indonesia in Jakarta, Udayana University in Bali, Hasanuddin University in Makassar, Haluoleo University in Kendari and Jambi University in Jambi.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] In January 2021, archaeologists announced the discovery of at least 45,500 years old cave art in Leang Tedongnge cave.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] According to the journal Science Advances, cave painting of a warty pig is the earliest evidence of human settlement of the region.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] An adult male pig, measuring 136 cm x 54 cm, was depicted with horn-like facial warts and two handprints above its hindquarters.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/archaeology-of-indonesia] According to co-author Adam Brumm, two other pigs that were partly preserved suggest that the wart pig was observing a fight between two of them.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/armadahan] The single outrigger float (*palangoy*) on the starboard side was either two bamboo poles lashed together or a flattened elongated beam.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/armadahan] It was connected to the hull by a length of bamboo around 6 m (20 ft) long, known as the *batangan*.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/armadahan] It also featured a counter-balance beam projecting off the port side known as the *paltek*.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/armadahan] The *batangan* is connected to the hull by a wooden outrigger beam collar, with braces on the forward, cross, and aft.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/armadahan] At the stern is a small socket for the rudder tiller.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/armadahan] Three or four other small holes are also drilled along the midcenter of the dugout to let the water enter the craft, allowing live fish to be stored in the hull when fishing.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/armadahan] These holes are also used to drain the craft when beached.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/armadahan] Each boat also has a cooking area on the aft, usually a wood or kerosene portable stove.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/armadahan] In modern times, these types of boats are usually motorized or paddled.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] They range from small dugout canoes to large lashed-lug plank-built vessels.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] Their hull configurations include monohulls as well as catamarans and outrigger boats (single-outrigger boats and trimarans).
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] Traditional sail types include a variety of distinctively Austronesian crab-claw and tanja configurations, though modern vessels are typically motorized.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] These vessels allowed the migrations of the Austronesian peoples during the Austronesian expansion (starting at around 3000 to 1500 BC from Taiwan and Island Southeast Asia) throughout the islands of the Indo-Pacific, reaching as far as Madagascar, New Zealand, and Easter Island.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] They were also used to establish trading routes, including the Austronesian maritime trade network which formed the maritime leg of the spice trade and later, the maritime silk road.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] Austronesians used distinctive sailing technologies, namely the catamaran, the outrigger ship, tanja sail and the crab claw sail.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] This allowed them to colonize a large part of the Indo-Pacific region during the Austronesian expansion starting at around 3000 to 1500 BC, and ending with the colonization of Easter Island and New Zealand in the 10th to 13th centuries AD.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] Prior to the 16th century Colonial Era, Austronesians were the most widespread ethnolinguistic group, spanning half the planet from Easter Island in the eastern Pacific Ocean to Madagascar in the western Indian Ocean.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] They also established vast maritime trading networks, among which is the Neolithic precursor to what would become the Maritime Silk Road.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] The simplest form of all ancestral Austronesian boats had five parts.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] The bottom part consists of a single piece of hollowed-out log.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] At the sides were two planks, and two horseshoe-shaped wood pieces formed the prow and stern.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] These were fitted tightly together edge-to-edge by sewing or with dowels inserted into holes in between, and then lashed to each other with ropes (made from rattan or fibre) wrapped around protruding lugs on the planks.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] This characteristic and ancient Austronesian boatbuilding practice is known as the "lashed-lug" technique.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] They were commonly caulked with pastes made from various plants as well as tapa bark and fibres which would expand when wet, further tightening joints and making the hull watertight.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] They formed the shell of the boat, which was then reinforced by horizontal ribs.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] Shipwrecks of Austronesian ships can be identified from this construction, as well as the absence of metal nails.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] Austronesian ships traditionally had no central rudders but were instead steered using an oar on one side.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] They also independently developed various sail types during the Neolithic, beginning with the crab claw sail (more usually called the "oceanic lateen" or the "oceanic sprit") at around 1500 BCE.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] They are used throughout the range of the Austronesian Expansion, from Maritime Southeast Asia, to Micronesia, Island Melanesia, Polynesia, and Madagascar.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] Crab claw sails are rigged fore-and-aft and can be tilted and rotated relative to the wind.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] They evolved from V-shaped perpendicular square sails in which the two spars converge at the base of the hull.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] The simplest form of the crab claw sail (also with the widest distribution) is composed of a triangular sail supported by two light spars (sometimes erroneously called "sprits") on each side.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] They were originally mastless, and the entire assembly was taken down when the sails were lowered.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] Austronesian rigs were used for double-canoe (catamaran), single-outrigger (on the windward side), or double-outrigger boat configurations, in addition to monohulls.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] There are several distinct types of crab claw rigs, but unlike western rigs, they do not have fixed conventional names.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] The need to propel larger and more heavily laden boats led to the increase in vertical sail.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] However this introduced more instability to the vessels.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] In addition to the unique invention of outriggers to solve this, the sails were also leaned backwards and the converging point moved further forward on the hull.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] This new configuration required a loose "prop" in the middle of the hull to hold the spars up, as well as rope supports on the windward side.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] This allowed more sail area (and thus more power) while keeping the center of effort low and thus making the boats more stable.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] The prop was later converted into fixed or removable canted masts where the spars of the sails were actually suspended by a halyard from the masthead.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] This type of sail is most refined in Micronesian proas which could reach very high speeds.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] These configurations are sometimes known as the "crane sprit" or the "crane spritsail".
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] Micronesian, Island Melanesian, and Polynesian single-outrigger vessels also used the canted mast configuration to uniquely develop shunting.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] In shunting vessels, both ends are alike, and the boat is sailed in either direction, but it has a fixed leeward side and a windward side.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] The boat is shunted from beam reach to beam reach to change direction, with the wind over the side, a low-force procedure.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] The bottom corner of the crab claw sail is moved to the other end, which becomes the bow as the boat sets off back the way it came.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] The mast usually hinges, adjusting the rake or angle of the mast.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] The crab claw configuration used on these vessels is a low-stress rig, which can be built with simple tools and low-tech materials, but it is extremely fast.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] On a beam reach, it may be the fastest simple rig.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] Another evolution of the basic crab claw sail is the conversion of the upper spar into a fixed mast.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] In Polynesia, this gave the sail more height while also making it narrower, giving it a shape reminiscent of crab pincers (hence "crab claw" sail).
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] This was also usually accompanied by the lower spar becoming more curved.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] The conversion of the prop to a fixed mast in the crab claw sail led to the much later invention of the tanja sail (also known variously and misleadingly as the canted square sail, canted rectangular sail, boomed lugsail, or balance lugsail).
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] Tanja sails were rigged similarly to crab claw sails and also had spars on both the head and the foot of the sails; but they were square or rectangular with the spars not converging into a point.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] They are generally mounted on one or two (rarely three or more) bipod or tripod masts, usually made from thick bamboo.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] The masts have curved heads with grooves for attaching the halyards.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] The lower part of two of the bamboo poles of the mast assembly have holes that are fitted unto the ends of a cross-wise length of timber on the deck, functioning like a hinge.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] The forward part of the mast assembly had a forelock.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] By unlocking it, the mast can be lowered across the ship.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] Despite the similarity of its appearance to western square rigs, the tanja is a fore-and-aft rig similar to a lugsail.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] The sail was suspended from the upper spar ("yard"), while the lower spar functioned like a boom.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] When set fore-and-aft, the spars extend forward of the mast by about a third of their lengths.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] When running before the wind, they are set perpendicular to the hull, similar to a square rig.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] The sail can be rotated around the mast (lessening the need for steering with the rudders) and tilted to move the center of pull forward or aft.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] The sail can even be tilted completely horizontally, becoming wing-like, to lift the bow above incoming waves.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] The sail is reefed by rolling it around the lower spar.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] In addition to the tanja sails, ships with the tanja rigs also have bowsprits set with a quadrilateral headsail, sometimes also canted as depicted in the Borobudur ships.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] In the colonial era, these were replaced by triangular western-style jibs (often several in later periods), and the tanja sails themselves were slowly replaced with western rigs like gaff rigs.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/austronesian-vessels] The following is an incomplete list of traditional Austronesian vessels.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/cirebon-shipwreck] The **Cirebon shipwreck** is a late 9th to 10th-century shipwreck discovered in 2003, in the Java Sea offshore of Cirebon, West Java, Indonesia.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/cirebon-shipwreck] The shipwreck contains a large amount of Chinese Yue ware, and is notable as important marine archaeology evidence of the Maritime Silk Road trading activity in Maritime Southeast Asia.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/cirebon-shipwreck] Local fishermen in the Java Sea acquired fragments of Chinese ceramics in their fishing nets back in 2003.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/cirebon-shipwreck] These ceramics were found at a depth of about 54 metres (177 ft), located about 100 kilometres (62 mi) from the port city of Cirebon.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/cirebon-shipwreck] The wreck was salvaged by a private company from 2004 to 2006.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/cirebon-shipwreck] About 250,000 artefacts were recovered, 65% of which consisted mainly of Chinese ceramics dated from Five Dynasties period of 10th-century Imperial China, and also other ceramics from other parts of Asia.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/cirebon-shipwreck] 10% was Near East and Indian glassware and gemstones, and the rest consisted of ingots, iron and other metals.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/cirebon-shipwreck] The ship was identified as a Western-Austronesian vessel of about 30 metres (98 ft) length, possibly built in the area around the Straits of Malacca.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/cirebon-shipwreck] A number of repairs visible on the remains of the hull imply that the vessel had been in use for a considerable time before her sinking.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/cirebon-shipwreck] The site of her foundering lies on a straight course from the Bangka Straits of southern Sumatra to the area around today's Semarang on Java.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/cirebon-shipwreck] An analysis of the Chinese coins in the cargo allows pinpointing the sinking to around 970 CE.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/cirebon-shipwreck] The salvaged artefacts were auctioned in 2006, subsequently salvagers split the sale 50-50 percent with Indonesian government.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/cirebon-shipwreck] Considering the importance of this find for the studies of economy and trade history, also marine archaeology; experts, historians and archaeologists urged the Indonesian government to keep and preserve most of the wreck's contents intact.
[src:cirebon-shipwreck/cirebon-shipwreck] The government decided to keep 10 percent of the 76,000 recovered artefacts intact as the collection of Indonesian museum.
